aws::graph::propositions: Robinson R22 Towing System
R22's manufactured after 1991 include a ¾" diameter tow ball mounted on the bottom of the fuselage.
The tow ball on the Robinson R22 is located near the front of the fuselage.
The tow ball on the Robinson R22 is offset slightly to the left.
A tow cart can be engaged with the tow ball on the Robinson R22.
A tug can be engaged with the tow ball on the Robinson R22.
The tow cart or tug can be used to lift the front of the helicopter.
Lifting the front of the helicopter clears the skids from the ground after wheels are installed.
Wheels are rotated to lift the rear of the skids on the Robinson R22.
The towing system makes it possible for a single person to move the Robinson R22 helicopter.
The Robinson R22 can be moved over significant distances using the towing system.
The Robinson R22 can be moved over not-level surfaces using the towing system.
Tow carts for the Robinson R22 are available with a variety of features.
Manual versions of tow carts place the ball mating device behind the wheels.
With manual tow carts, the operator engages the ball then pushes down on the handle to lift the nose.
Some tow carts provide a repurposed car-style hydraulic jack to lift the nose.
Some tow carts provide an electric jack to lift the nose.
Tow carts are available with no motive power.
Tow carts are available with a gas engine.
Tow carts are available with one electric motor.
Tow carts are available with two electric motors.
Electric motors on tow carts are operated from one or two batteries.

text:
R22’s manufactured after 1991 include a ¾” diameter tow ball mounted on the bottom of the fuselage, near the front and offset slightly to the left. A tow cart or tug can be engaged with the ball and then used to lift the front of the helicopter to clear the skids from the ground after the wheels are installed and rotated to lift the rear of the skids.  This makes it possible for a single person to move the helicopter, even over significant distances or not-level surfaces.
Tow carts are available with a variety of features.  There exist manual versions which place the ball mating device behind the wheels so the operator engages the ball then pushes down on the handle to lift the nose.  Others provide a repurposed car-style hydraulic jack to lift the nose.  Others provide an electric jack.  
Tow carts are available with no motive power, a gas engine or one or two electric motors operated from one or two batteries.
